english:
  title: Preface to Poems on the Spring Pavilion
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Minister Ha, upon his appointment as Regional Commander of Jeolla, issued this proclamation: "What troubles our people and brings worry to the realm is none other than the Japanese raiders. They are skilled in water routes, swift to attack and quick to retreat, making them difficult for defenders to counter—yet I have come to understand their ways." Thereupon, mounted upon his horse, he swore an oath with his troops, advanced with sounding drums and unfurled banners, deploying forces along the coast above and below. The enemy, unable to gauge his strength, gradually withdrew of their own accord. Yet the Minister, unwilling to rest in complacency, kept his soldiers encamped beyond the walls, positioned at vital passes to guard against unforeseen calamity.

    It was the sixth month, in the southernmost reaches where sea mists exhale their sultry breath and clouds shimmer with heat. The air pressed down from above, moisture rose from below, and all suffered from the oppressive warmth. One day, the Minister climbed to a high place and beheld the great river flowing beneath, ringed by mountains whose peaks interlocked like screens, dotted with sandbars and islets. As clouds dispersed and mists scattered, the view opened wide. The sweltering heat suddenly gave way to coolness, the dampness to clarity—as if one had plunged burning hands into crystal waters. A rapture seized him, as though riding upon the long wind itself, ascending into the boundless sky.

    His attendants and officers, delighting in this revelation, urged the Minister to construct a pavilion upon this spot. Unable to refuse their unanimous wish, he sent idle soldiers to gather timber and cut thatch. Before a day had passed, the structure stood complete. When a visitor asked what name should grace this pavilion, the Minister replied, "I have long called myself Spring Pavilion. Since I have built this structure, let it bear that name."

    The visitor later spoke to others, saying: "Remarkable is the Minister's naming! Built in summer's height, this pavilion draws cool breezes from heaven's edge and channels refreshing air into one's very breast. The body grows light and nimble, the spirit calm and expansive—one forgets entirely that the season burns and the land lies scorched. When autumn winds arise and the silver moon shines bright, when wild geese cry over distant sandbars and lonely sails rest at remote anchorages, when dark clouds refuse to part and river and sky merge into one, fishermen in their reed cloaks wade through what seems like snow. These too are the pavilion's sublime moments. As for wildflowers blooming and birds singing in spring and summer—these are merely the pleasures of a single season. Yet the pavilion commands such beauty through all four seasons, and the Minister has chosen to honor but one. What could his reason be?"

    One learned visitor explained: "Heaven possesses the Four Seasons to complete the year; humans possess the Four Sprouts to govern their nature. Though each season claims its portion, Spring pervades all four—just as each sprout manifests one virtue, yet Humaneness encompasses them all. Thus we say: Spring is the sprouting of Spring; Summer is Spring's growth; Autumn is Spring's fruition; Winter is Spring's storage. Humaneness is the love of Humaneness; Righteousness is Humaneness's ordering; Propriety is Humaneness's reverence; Wisdom is Humaneness's knowing. What in time is Spring, in human nature is Humaneness—these are one principle.

    "In Heaven, this principle flows ceaselessly without interruption, spreading forth as the Four Seasons, weaving through all beings. Change is endless, generation never ceases—this is Spring as the Humaneness of Heaven and Earth. In humans, this manifests as impartiality and joy, unmarred by the slightest selfishness or resentment. Its accumulation brings harmony; its expression brings flourishing. Applied to oneself, the body finds peace; extended to the family, parent and child grow close. In all dealings with things, nothing fails to find its proper place. This is Humaneness as one person's Spring.

    "Once, Zhu Guangting called Cheng Mingdao a spring breeze—nor was his word false. O Spring! O Humaneness! How profound is this highest virtue! Only those who know the Way can partake of this. Such is the Minister's intention. Those who ascend this pavilion should not merely seek the pleasures of sight-seeing. Rather, they should seek the mind of the gentleman embodying Humaneness, and further still, the creative heart of Heaven and Earth. Only then will they understand why the pavilion is called Spring, and truly share in the Minister's joy."

    The visitor replied, "Indeed, indeed." And so all composed verses to commemorate the occasion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Four Sprouts' (四端) refer to compassion, shame, respect, and right and wrong—proto-virtues that germinate in human nature according to Mencius and Neo-Confucian philosophy.
  - key: ''
    value: Cheng Mingdao (程明道, 1032-1085) was a celebrated Neo-Confucian philosopher whose gentle virtue inspired Zhu Guangting's metaphor comparing him to a spring breeze.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''Spring Pavilion'' is a deliberate philosophical pun: though constructed in summer and situated in a hot coastal region, it represents the principle of Humaneness that transcends temporal and spatial limitations.'
